# Line-ending discipline for xion-os.
#
# Property promised: every byte of every hashed artifact is identical on
# every checkout, on every operating system, forever. Without this file
# a fresh Windows clone under `core.autocrlf=true` would write CRLF into
# the working tree, causing `xion-verify {covenant,invariants,soul,…}`
# to report FAIL on files whose content is substantively unchanged.
# That would be a false negative on a constitutional check — unacceptable.
#
# Invariants touched: 14 (Crypto-Agility Mandate). SHA-256 is byte-exact;
# so the bytes must themselves be deterministic across checkouts.
#
# Verification: after cloning on any OS, `xion-verify --self-test &&
# xion-verify all --allow-not-yet-sealed` returns OK without any local
# renormalization step.
#
# Deprecation: if a future policy ever deliberately ships CRLF artifacts,
# move them to an explicit binary track in this file; never weaken the
# default.

# Default: treat every text file with LF line endings in the working tree.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Belt-and-suspenders for everything the verifier hashes or reads.
*.md       text eol=lf
*.txt      text eol=lf
*.py       text eol=lf
*.toml     text eol=lf
*.yml      text eol=lf
*.yaml     text eol=lf
*.json     text eol=lf
*.sol      text eol=lf
*.lua      text eol=lf
*.sh       text eol=lf
*.cfg      text eol=lf
*.ini      text eol=lf

# Binaries: keep git's hands off.
*.png      binary
*.jpg      binary
*.jpeg     binary
*.gif      binary
*.webp     binary
*.ico      binary
*.pdf      binary
*.zip      binary
*.tar      binary
*.gz       binary
*.whl      binary
*.woff     binary
*.woff2    binary
